3":"1223","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","1244":"1244","1331":"1331","1309":"1309","1218":"1218","Tong, Shropshire, England":"Tong, Shropshire, England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1253–":"1253–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1244–1279":"1244–1279","1253–Male":"1253–Deceased","1260–1303":"1260–1303","1266–1331":"1266–1331","1258–1279":"1258–1279","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1218–1272":"1218–1272","1223–1309":"1223–1309","1253":"1253","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","27 APR 1272":"27 April 1272","1303":"1303","1258":"1258","1279":"1279","1223":"1223","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","1244":"1244","1331":"1331","1309":"1309","1218":"1218","Tong, Shropshire, England":"Tong, Shropshire, England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pembridge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Pembridge (Herefs), which is recorded as  <i>Penebrug(g)e</i> from the 11th to 14th centuries. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pena</i> + Old English  <i>brycg</i> ‘bridge’. In some cases the surname may be from Pen Bridge in Shipley (Sussex), which derives from an uncertain first element + Old English  <i>brycg</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pember","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of <b>Pamber</b>, a habitational name from a place in Hampshire named Pamber, from Old English <i>penn</i> ‘fold, enclosure’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Pembridge I was born in 1253, in Evesham, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry de Pembrugge, was 35 and his mother, Elizabeth Gamage, was 31. He married Euphemia Lingen in 1274, in Evesham, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He was buried in Evesham, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1253–":"1253–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1244–1279":"1244–1279","1253–Male":"1253–Surnud","1260–1303":"1260–1303","1266–1331":"1266–1331","1258–1279":"1258–1279","1275–1300":"1275–1300","1218–1272":"1218–1272","1223–1309":"1223–1309","1253":"1253","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1260":"1260","27 APR 1272":"27. aprill 1272","1303":"1303","1258":"1258","1279":"1279","1223":"1223","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","1244":"1244","1331":"1331","